## DNA methylation

	* All cells have the same DNA but different epigenetics
	* Lots of various processes
* [x] DNA Methylation is one of those epigenetic processes
	* Methylation occurs at Citosine guanine base pair
	* CpG islands are grouped CpG sites
* [x] DNA methylation is measured by bisulfite sequencing

# Related work
- [ ] **The Problem**
      Measure how healthy someone is/ measure his epigenetic age?
	- we predict change of methylation with time (bio-age), not disease
		- Healthspan vs Lifespan?
			- age is your probability to get sick/die?
		- there're diseases that make you age and there're diseases that just attack your immune system
			- Cancer is attacking not aging. CKD same. But Down syndrome does age you faster
		- 
- [ ] **Why this Problem**
      This can be applied to understand actual aging better
	- evaluating rejuvenation,  
	- differences between the aging and not-aging diseases
	- age is a key risk factor in many diseases so useful
- [ ] **Attempts**
      Using omics data because the problem is so complex
	- [ ] First generation methylation clocks explicitly predict the chronological age
		- Started by accident in 2011, noticing the relation when looking at saliva methylation [@bocklandt2011epigenetic] [@bocklandt2011epigenetic](@bocklandt2011epigenetic.md) 
		- Thought of applications in forensic science, archeology
		- Then Hannum publishes 71 CpG clock [@hannum2013genome](@hannum2013genome.md) 
		- In the same year, Horvath publishes multi-tissue clock [@horvath2013dna](@horvath2013dna.md)
			- Actually shows that age offset correlates with some diseases which affect aging like cancer and down syndrome
				- You don't train explicitly for the diseases but you happen to get them
				- [ ] cancer results are not that sure
			- Can predict on different tissue types despite being trained on other
		- Since then, other clock that try to reduce the number of CpGs [@weidner2014aging](@weidner2014aging.md) or overtraining [@zhang2019improved](@zhang2019improved.md)
	- [ ] Second generation (composite clocks) don't focus on chronoligal age but the mortality
		- Started with [@zhang2017dna](@zhang2017dna.md) who focuses on mortality risk
		- Then [@levine2018epigenetic](@levine2018epigenetic.md) (PhenoAge) and [@lu2019dna](@lu2019dna.md) (GrimAge) propose composite clocks
		- Recent development of using time-series data to predict pace of aging [@belsky2020quantification](@belsky2020quantification.md)
- [ ] **The Gap**
      They predict instead of explaining/observing. They explain all the biological variability while we actually want that
	- [ ] First Generation breaks down as you have more data/complex model
		- Letting ML to select the best sites for chronoligal age prediction is not optimal for understanding the change in methylation value
			- the coefficient is not related with actual slope
			- The more you train, the more accurate you are (explain the variability) and you lose the information. like noticed in [@zhang2019improved](@zhang2019improved.md)
			- You get better chronological age predictions and you don't want that - you want biological age
			- Horvath hit a sweet spot of having not too much data
				- he still leaves plenty of variability
			- It's not overfitting because its transferable
			- ![horvath_age](horvath_age.png)
		- Unsenstive to diseases present when you have tons of data because the model accomodates for them
			- You can get sites that predict disease/lifestyle instead of age (smoking)
				- ![image](data:image/png;base64,)
				- Show figure with constant site predicting smokers #figure 
		- The measures they're using are crude
			- Age offset doesn't differentiate in between normal aging/technical error
			- Person 10 years older when 20 years old and a person 10 years older when 60 years old is different but not here
			- ![Image caption](age-offset-problem.png)
		- You cannot differentiate between the technical error/hypomethylation and actual aging.
			- Dan's paper about adding hypomethylation
	- [ ] Second generation (composite) clocks are predicting for more than age
		- You signal gets lost
			- Eric's CKD study with Horvath not showing anything and PhenoAge showing a lot
		- Once you start picking other age-related biomarkers, you're biased by what you chose. You don't let data choose
- [ ] **The Solution (Contribution)**
	- Probabilistic, mathematical approach
		- Explicitly model what you're after
		- Give confidence in the parameters
	- Selecting only the sites changing with time
	- Modelling persons deviations and model comparison
	- Extending the model to account for aging speed and bias

## Selecting time-dependent sites
- [ ] **What?** 
	Selecting sites where time explains change in methylation
	- We look at the changes of methylation value with time
	- We use age for the time
	- We select sites that can explain the variability of methylation values
		- Show a figure of a nice, linear site #figure #todo 
	- We don't want sites that stay constant or are blobs
		- Show a figure with all site types #figure 
		- ![site_types](site_types.png)
- [ ] **Why?** 
	Time related sites are useful for getting age deviation
	- You're left with sites rich in information (explained variance) which is good for age normality
		- If the site is not changing with age, you can't tell the difference in between the old and young person
	- Leaving this to ML can result in selecting sites that don't predict age but predict a disease/lifestyle
		- That's bad because we want to be 
- [ ] **How?** 
	We perform non-parametric selection based on statistics
	- We fit a line and look at the variance explained by the fit (r2)
	- We set a threshold because that's where most of the crap stays out
	- In general, also the sites with extremes of variance are not useful - both the too much and too little
		- Too much are multimodal (making sure by counting peaks), too little are constant #figure
		- ![Pasted image 20220908092318](Pasted%20image%2020220908092318.png)
- [ ] **Problems?**
      

## Modelling person age normality
- [ ] **What?** 
	Measuring the probability of methylation value given the age mean
	- The further you are from the mean, the more unlikely you are
	- We normalize the likelihoods for comparison across the whole time spectrum
		- Show a plot with likelihoods vs the relative likelihoods #figure 
		- ![Pasted image 20220908092533](Pasted%20image%2020220908092533.png)
- [ ] **Why?** 
	Probabilistic approach gives us a confidence measure/interval
	- We are able to see what is a normal and what is a far deviation
	- ML approach would return everything as an error
	- We can experiment with different models and tell which fit data better
- [ ] **How?** 
	We compare ordinary linear regression with weighted  and experiment with different value distributions
	- Ordinary linear regression assumes normal error around the mean
		- Show a site plotted with constant variance #figure
		- Show model with just constant variance #equation
	- Weighted linear regression in our case assumes variance changing linearly with time
		- Show a site with linear variance #figure 
		- ![Pasted image 20220908092632](Pasted%20image%2020220908092632.png)
		- Show equation with variance slope #equation 
		- ![Pasted image 20220908113447](Pasted%20image%2020220908113447.png)
		- ![Pasted image 20220908100614](Pasted%20image%2020220908100614.png)
		- We limit the variance slope to be only positive
	- Beta distribtion doesn't violate the rule that methylation value is \[0,1\]
		- Show a cpg site plot in which you sample the pdf to show its values and compare normal vs beta #figure #todo
	- We select optimal model based on AIC
		- Show equations for AIC relative weight #equation 

## Predicting aging speed
- [ ] **What?**
      Having a measure of how quickly someone is aging and whether he has a global age offset
	- Aging speed is his increase of methylation value per year, bias is his technical error
		- Show a comparison of a person that is faster but no bias vs a person with bias but normal speed #figure
	- It's not acceleration, it only means you accelerated in the past
- [ ] **Why?**
      We have more information than jus the age offset
	- We can tell his future instead of just the offset
	- We can differentiate in between someone who is just hypo-methylated (or technical error) and someone who is actually aging fast
		- Dan's paper about adding global hypomethylation
		- Cancer is decreasing the methylation while not aging faster?
		- In ML approach, you combine the two.
		- Relate to the figure from **What?** question
	- We can provide confidence of the parameters using the posterior distribution
- [ ] **How?**
      We model a person with a single alpha and beta parameter
	- For a single participant, we look across all the sites and estimate his global speed and bias
		- We already know the slopes and variances for sites
		- Show the model with alpha and beta #equation 
		- $$P(m|t)= \prod_i\mathcal{N}(m; \space \alpha^ja_it + b_i + \beta^j, \space c_it) $$
	- We check by model comparison if adding speed and bias is beneficial
	- We evaluate the posterior distribution to give confidence
		- Show a graph with posterior distribuions (to the sites from the **What?** questions) #figure  #todo 
		- ![Pasted image 20220908093103](Pasted%20image%2020220908093103.png)
		- ![Pasted image 20220908093129](Pasted%20image%2020220908093129.png)
- [ ] **Problems?**
       We are limited by cross-sectional data
	- For aging speed we assume constant acceleration. If we had previous timepoints we could model the accuracy
	- Bias cancels out across the increasing and decreasing sites and we assume a balance of increasing vs decreasing
		- Cancels out because if you age faster, you're above in increasing and below in decreasing
